text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Aryaman Xs comment on this

Startups are built like musical scales.

Were building ours in chords. 


Not traditional linear pathways, but finding harmony within constraints. 

Thats exactly what our MVP taught us, and keeps teaching us. 

Building in Ohio, we had no idea what the usual startup playbook was. I learned what a coffee chat is when my friend described theirs two months ago. 

So we learned to play with the cards weve been dealt: 

- Locally hosting LLMs because API costs wouldve killed us.
- Testing with the same community we built through our music production club.
- Growing on LinkedIn to expose the problem to the people who could actually help us solve it. 

Every constraint forced us to get creative. Every limitation became a feature. 

Thats when I realized: dont raise. 

Not yet. 

Not until youve exhausted every resource around you. 

Fundraising is the easy answer. Building with constraints is the hard one. 

But the hard ones teach you what your product actually needs to be. 

That being said, this chapter is about to close. 

Our MVP is coming. Weve proven the thesis with almost nothing.

Now its time to scale what works. 

Were officially raising in 2026. 

If youre building right now and think you need to raise to make progress, take a moment to reflect.

Exhaust your constraints first. They'll teach you more than capital ever could.

Launchmas #23

text.text: Rayyan Aquino commented on this

your New Years resolution will fail.
im not saying that to hate either.

the stats do it for me:
80% of resolutions fail by February and only about 9% ever succeed
why?
because what sounded "exciting" on January 1st gets buried by real life
school. work. stress. boredom.

the first few months are brutal
but if you can just make it to February, you dramatically increase your odds
not because February is magical
but because most people quit before they can build any long term habits

for most, resolutions arent about doing but about talking
people make a big announcement, a big post,
I AM GOING TO DO THIS".
then nothing happens
the resolution becomes a performance
something just to tell other people
not something to actually do

thats why Im not sharing my resolution
you wont hear a crazy goal
you wont see a hype post
however you will see the effects
not what I tell everyone, but what actually happens because of it

is your resolution for you or your followers?

text.text: Rayyan Aquino commented on this

Connection is the only real cheat code left.


In 2025, tech made it stupid easy todisconnect.
but last week it did the opposite.

Less than 7 days ago, i reconnected with a old friend whos now at CMU studying ECE + AI/ML. Sam Mathew.

Today, we spent 6 hours fixing THAT problem every bay area kid is coping with:
- study ruts & burn out

6 hours of locking in.
a cursor subscription
and marugame udon as the fuel.

We werent the only ones locking in though.

The table in front of us? sophmores at Monta Vista High School running coding classes and a hackathon every 2 weeks.

The table behind us was two seniors collaborating with robert lee and Carnegie Mellon Universitys lunar projects like it was nothing.

I ended up connecting with the MV sophomores.
one of them is a cracked iOS + Android dev with a shipped app. Jason He
thats not someday networking. thats how the bay area compounds in real-time


Theres one question I cant shut up about
what are YOU building?

Because none of this happens without:
- sending the DM.
- taking the call.
- sitting at the table next to the other builders.

Nothing is possible without connection.
if youre reading this, introduce yourself in the comments and tell me what youre building next weekend.


~ aayushya

i got 5 YC company interviews @ 16 and landed an offer
you really have to fight like hell


when you're as young as I am, your biggest edge is probably that no one takes you seriously

over the past month i've been applying, following up, posting in public, and pitching to founders who definitely did not have teenager on their meeting agenda

yeah as you can tell it wasn't a sooth ride
it was 66-67 applications sent
it was getting ghosted by 90 percent of them
it was studying their entire icp and biz model 5 min before the call
it was like studying for ap physics last second all over again

but wait.. they called back!??!?!
"wait broski u can come work for me"

and suddenly being 16 aint a barrier
its me being a battering ram (clash reference im the evo vers ifykyk)

lesson learned:
hesitant? do it anyways
progress looks like embarrassment
and if you aint doubting yourself, you not even dreaming big enough

super grateful for every no
super grateful for every crack in my confidence
and super awake for whats next

if your age hasnt flattened you yet
you playing it too safe

much love
-luke

text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Fay Wus comment on this

Get me a whiteboard and Ill build your entire startup. 

I have no idea what it is about whiteboarding, but I just reach this oddly satisfying flow state where I can accurately map out systems, create five-year plans, and find hidden workflows. 

The weird thing is, nothing on the board makes any sense. 

Arrows pointing left and right. 

Terms circled and dates starred. 

Messy blurbs and explanations.

Yet when I get the team together and explain how everything works, suddenly it clicks for all of us. 

Solutions emerge through the spontaneous chaos. 

My #1 recommendation if youre a founder: get a whiteboard. Multiple if you can. 

 Because when you start mapping it out. 

Chaos will become clarity.

Launchmas #12

text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Jan Sings comment on this

Let it simmer.

It's not all "cook or be cooked."

The best progress is sometimes no progress.

I thought building slowly meant I'd run out of momentum fast. That slowing down meant falling behind.

But patience is where the connections happen.

It's laughing with your co-founder about a bug that became a feature. Chatting in the LockedIn group chat and seeing how other builders think. Catching up with a mentor who asks the one question that reframes everything.

Those little moments? They bring the biggest breakthroughs.

That's how we realized Virtuoso isn't just for new learners, but even for the professionals who want to gain a little dynamic edge.

Taking time to see that connection is what turned our vision from "music education tool" into "the Duolingo for music producers."

I'm not cooking a 996. I'm taking occasional moments to appreciate and recalibrate.

Because sometimes, you just need to let things simmer.

Launchmas #24

text.text: Rayyan Aquino commented on this

Day 4 of building the most UNFUNDABLE startup in the world.

In just three days we got 90% of our MVP done. Itll be ready for our first batch of private beta testing by this weekend.

We have no idea if our core feature that we developed is something people would even want to use, but theres no better way to find out than to ship it and get real feedback.

Heres what weve built:
At a set time everyday
For just a minute
A video call rings with a friend on the other side.

You wont know who the friend is until you join and the call automatically ends in 60 seconds.

This way, you build up the habit of ALWAYS staying in touch with people you truly care about. Even if youre busy, just a minute out of your day goes a long way.

What are you predictions on how this will go? 
Let me know if youd like to test it out :)

text.text: Rayyan Aquino commented on this

IMA B****



While some people are complaining, scrolling, or waiting for motivation, we move. Christmas Day. Laptops out. Grinding anyway.

Were not crying about missing out.
Were not stressed about FOMO.
Were not pretending its easy.

And that, is the choice.

Do you want to complain.
Do you want to quit.
Do you want to stop when it gets uncomfortable.

Or do you want to build something while everyone else is resting.

People love to say hustle culture is toxic (biggest excuse EVER) And yeah, burning yourself out for no reason is dumb. But the truth is subjective. Some people will call staying up until 4am insane. Others will call it necessary. It all depends on what youre trying to build and how bad you want it.

We chose progress.

What do you choose?
